The person who ended up taking our picture was a German naturalist, visiting
to photograph Montana alpine and tundra wildflowers. He was quite delighted we
asked him to take our picture, and received a T-shirt from the group to
remember us by. He also took pictures of us with his own camera, saying they
would be published when he returned home.

Here's a topo of the Roadside Park at the summit:

{% flickr-img :photo-id 36256381991
              :album-id 72157684801453550
              :user forgottenroadsmx
              :width 2048 %}

At this point, the group was splitting off -- everyone continuing southward on
212 ... so to Cody, some to Cooke City. After that, the group was splitting
even further, including trips to Alaska, the Moab, Yellowstone, and the Black
Hills. I was the only one who would be returning to Red Lodge, so after
bidding farewell, I was riding back down.

{% flickr-img :photo-id 35993184130
              :album-id 72157684801453550
              :user forgottenroadsmx
              :width 2048 %}

I missed the group, but the turns were even more fun this time around :-) It
also gave me a chance to stop and grab some shots of some of the things I'd
missed on the way up:

{% flickr-img :photo-id 35039037024
              :album-id 72157684801453550
              :user forgottenroadsmx
              :width 1536 %}

In one of the pull-offs, I saw a Triumph all decked out, so I pulled over and
ended up having a really long chat with its rider. He's a local who comes up
to the mountains to ride all the time. He shared a big chunk of his recent
life story, including possible plans of packing up and traveling around the
U.S., looking for new territory and good rides. I wished him well, and
continued down the mountain.

{% flickr-img :photo-id 36389838425
              :album-id 72157684801453550
              :user forgottenroadsmx
              :width 2048 %}

After getting off the bike, I was delighted to see the evidence of the day's
